
Milestones (M1 → M8) with exact “what’s next”


These are ordered so you always know the next build step. Don’t skip ahead.


M1 — Skeleton + DB connectivity


Outcome: repo builds, both apps start, DB reachable.

•	Create 3 modules: core, api, worker
•	Choose Postgres (recommended) + Docker Compose (optional)
•	Add a simple health endpoint in API: GET /health
•	Verify both apps can connect to DB


You’re done when

•	API starts + /health returns OK
•	Worker starts (even if it does nothing yet)





M2 — Core domain + Job table


Outcome: your platform has a real Job model + persistence shape.

•	In core.domain: create Job, JobStatus, JobType
•	Define minimum fields: id, type, status, payload, result, error, attempt, maxAttempts, createdAt, updatedAt, lockedBy, lockedAt
•	Create DB schema migration (Flyway/Liquibase) for jobs table
•	In core.repository: JobRepository interface (only method signatures, no Spring here)


You’re done when

•	DB has jobs table
•	You can create a Job object in code and it compiles in all modules





M3 — API can submit & query jobs (no worker yet)


Outcome: you can create jobs and retrieve them through REST.

•	In core.dto: CreateJobRequest, CreateJobResponse, JobView
•	In api.persistence: implement JobRepository (JPA/JdbcTemplate)
•	In api.service: JobSubmissionService.createJob(...)
•	In api.controller: POST /jobs, GET /jobs/{id}, GET /jobs?status=&type=


You’re done when

•	You can POST /jobs and get a jobId
•	GET /jobs/{id} returns QUEUED job data





M4 — Worker can claim a job (the hard “real systems” part)


Outcome: you’ve solved “no double processing.”

•	In worker.claiming: JobClaimer.claimNextJobs(workerId, limit)
o	Atomically transition QUEUED → RUNNING
o	Set lockedBy, lockedAt
•
•	In worker.polling: JobPoller loop calls claimer every X ms
•	Add logs for lifecycle transitions


You’re done when

•	Worker picks up a queued job and marks it RUNNING
•	If you run two workers, the same job is not claimed twice





M5 — Dispatch + handler interface


Outcome: worker can execute “job types” cleanly.

•	In worker.handler: JobHandler interface:
o	JobType supports()
o	JobResult handle(Job job) (your design)
•
•	In worker.dispatch: JobDispatcher routes job → handler by type
•	Add a “demo” handler (no CSV yet) like NOOP or ECHO_PAYLOAD
•	Worker sets job to SUCCEEDED and stores result


You’re done when

•	A queued ECHO_PAYLOAD job ends up SUCCEEDED with result saved





M6 — Retries + backoff + failure recording


Outcome: reliability features that interviewers care about.

•	On handler exception:
o	increment attempt
o	if attempt < maxAttempts → back to QUEUED with availableAt (add column) OR a simple nextRunAt
o	else → FAILED and store error
•
•	Implement exponential backoff (simple formula is fine)
•	Update claiming to only claim jobs whose nextRunAt <= now


You’re done when

•	You can submit a job designed to fail and watch retries happen
•	After max attempts it becomes FAILED





M7 — First real “vehicle”: CSV job type (end-to-end)


Outcome: platform becomes “useful”, not just infra.

•	In API:
o	POST /csv/jobs (upload file, store it, create CSV_PROCESS job)
•
•	In worker:
o	CsvProcessJobHandler parses + validates + produces output + summary
•
•	Add endpoints:
o	GET /csv/jobs/{id}/summary
o	GET /csv/jobs/{id}/result (download)
•


You’re done when

•	Upload CSV → job runs → you can download output and see a summary





M8 — “Resume polish” + production vibes


Outcome: this looks like a real system.

•	Add Swagger/OpenAPI (optional)
•	Add structured logging (jobId, jobType)
•	Add metrics counts (optional)
•	Add Docker compose: Postgres + API + Worker
•	Write README:
o	architecture diagram
o	how to run
o	tradeoffs (DB queue vs Redis later)
o	failure/retry behavior
•


You’re done when

•	Someone can clone and run it in <10 minutes
•	README explains it clearly





“After M8” expansion path (how you add more services later)


You have two clean options:

1.	Add more job types (recommended first): just new handlers in worker.handler + optional endpoints in api.controller
2.	Add separate microservices that submit jobs to the same DB (later): e.g., a “notifications service” that only calls POST /jobs and reads status

